doctype html
html(lang="en")
  head
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width,initial-scale=1" />
    title HTTP Status Club - Test HTTP response status codes for your API calls.
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Maven+Pro">
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Rokkitt">
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="./styles/styles.css">
    <style>
      | html { background-color: #71C597; color: #292929; font-family: "Maven Pro"; font-weight: 600;}
      | h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6 { font-family: "Rokkitt";}
      | code {background: #ccc; color: #292929; padding: 4px 6px; border-radius: 8px;}
      | header {display: flex; align-items: center;}
      | .name {margin: 5px 0 0 12px;}
      | .logo {width: 80px; padding: 8px;}
      | .tagline {font-family: "Maven Pro";}
    </style>
  body
    header
      div.logo
        img(src="./images/logo.svg")
      h1.name HTTP Status Club
    h2.tagline Where Status is all that matters.
    p This service allows you to test how your code handles various HTTP response status codes. Just include the code you would like to test in the testing URL.
    p Example: <a href="/code/200">https://httpstatus.club/code/200</a>
    p This will return a status of <code>200 OK</code>.
    h2 The following codes are fully supported.
    table
      each item in data
        if item.fullySupported === true
          tr
            td
              | #[a(href=item.sourceUrl target="_blank") #{item.code}]
              | #{item.reasonPhrase}
    h2 The following codes are partially supported.
    p Most of these will return the correct response code, but probably won't return the expected headers, body, etc. Use them at your own peril!
    table
      each item in data
        if !item.fullySupported
          tr
            td
              | #[a(href=item.sourceUrl target="_blank") #{item.code}]
              | #{item.reasonPhrase}